t laughable if it weren’t so serious. The main problem is that schools have been incorrectly identified as the culprits in the disadvantage that children from areas of disadvantage suffer. And the one main saviour in the sorry state of these children’s l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ives: their local school, with their familiar and experienced teacher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s – this actual saviour has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been accused and even found guilty of neglect and incompetence. </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is unbelievably ignorant on the part of the powers that be. They have removed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from the mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">st needy the one institution in the area that they live in that could have protected them from the child abuse in all its forms, and the rest.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The damage really started with the introduction of Ofsted and of League Tables [both crude</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unscientific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">], and n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">either of them in any way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">able to gauge the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">true measures of a schools’ worth.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The first academy in Leeds was the David Young Academy. It replaced two closed, one a mixed C of E school, and one a single sex secular boys’ school. In one year it excluded mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re children than all other Leeds schools, and all these other schools were obliged to pick up the excluded children, who then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">saw </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">depressed their results in general [including attendance]. These children were now well out of the reach of the teachers who h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ad cared for them, in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a personal and an academic way, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the kids </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were sent spiralling down to the PRUs, taking out the next group of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> schools on their way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> including working with sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have attended nearly all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Leeds consultation meetings for academisation. And the process in every case was, in my opinion, corrupt and totally lacking in academic rigour. In particular the situation at South Leeds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">High </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">School was one of the most dishonest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This newly made school had only just </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recovered from the merger of two very different schools [Merlyn Rees - very white ex-working class, and Matthew Murray, largely Asian], enduring at first some racial tensions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">After some rocky early </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">moments, the Ofsted team in 200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [ish]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> said progress was being and that the last thing this school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was any more change and in particular to be made into an academy. </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Leeds at that time was suffering from having a private educa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion company inflicted upon and they were only too happy to join forces with the ten Labour govt and continue with the process towards academisation. The public consultation was packed with general public, local residents, union representatives, staff and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">students etc. I went partly as an informed education campaigner and partly because two close friends and my oldest daughter worked there. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There were many articulate and emotional speeches. Nobody spoke in favour of academisation from the floor. The staff </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were still in recovery from the merger; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">another upheaval was unimaginable. The vote from the floor was unanimous against the idea. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When Garforth Academy took over running South Leeds Academy [the only academy not to change the school’s name</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,and the only g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ood thing in that process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the staff were torn: stay with the families they knew, or acknowledge they had served their time and get out. Also they recognised that they had done everything they could in these deprived areas, and the new management [which i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncluded the old headteacher] was kidding itself if they thought either that they could do be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tter, or that good exam grades wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s always a priority for “disadvantaged” children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [Children were bussed the 15 miles from South Leeds Academy to Garforth Academy t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o study and take the quick fix extra GCSEs in order allegedly to benefit the kids, but actually to demonstrate “improvement”. On one occasion I arrived, as agreed and paid for by the school in order to  help rehearse and record their GCSE Music performance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s, only to find that half the class had been taken to Garforth during the Music lesson].</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The head, who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> had previously</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> argued against academisation decided to offer to stay on as head, in the hope and belief that he could minimise the damage. But already th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e staff, previously quite </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">long-serving,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> now started to leave in droves; after over ten years three, the head of Science was on her way to being Science advisor in Dubai; my daughter back to university [high quality dedicated staff]. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When the head retired </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then the bullying really started, and teachers who had been at Merlyn Rees/MatthewMurray/South Leeds for decades either succumbed to depression, or left at the first opportunity.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Fif</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ty left this summer. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To sum, the effect of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">forcing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academisation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on an un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">willing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> South Leeds was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o misunderstand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the nature of the intake;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fail to appreciate that exam grades only are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a very poor measure of a school;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not to understand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">publicly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to attack and pillory a school staff would only demoralise and lose them, not make them more effective. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These process was repeated around Leeds. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role wil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">l work as the programme expands. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Sec of State has no experience, no true knowledge, is unsuited and is unfit for this purpose. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">He or she will have absolutely no time to look at each “failing” academy, and actually, it is a false concept. Academies ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e replacing “failing schools”, and there was, bizarrely, no expectation from gov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ernments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that academies themselves could fail. Otherwise why put whole communities through the trauma of such an upheaval. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the other hand, people with experience of changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of a similar nature did expect them to be no better in the terms that this country judges our ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ucational establishments. Union</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> representatives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in particular have a vast experience in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">such situations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, spending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, sacrificing even</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> lives to looki</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng after others who come unstuck in the system. The support and advice that unions could offer to governments would make our education system purr along, but the most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the public see of them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [unions]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is not the day to day care of teachers etc, but the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">times of frustration when strikes are the last and only option. Governments treat unions as the enemy, possibly because they feel criticised by them and support the media and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill-informed public opinion whenever it fancies a bit of union-bashing. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Or just l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ooking for someone to blame.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As for the question – what role should the Sec of State have, as the programme expands of intervening in failing academies. Well, that should not be the question. What s/he really should do is let them revert to the support of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their local education authority and become schools again. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The functions and responsibilities of local authorities in respect to academies and free schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">They are evidently expected to intervene and support on a zero budget. Their local knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">goes to waste. People lose jobs. It destabilises cities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Personally I am part of the local music service, and I run a central band with instruments bought by the money that once came to the local authority and now goes straight to academies, and wages to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our two staff from the same fund. Many peripatetic teachers have QTS and are experienced in school-teaching, making us superbly qualified to provide that extra specialist music teaching. However, like many other authorities we are now consulting on having </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our pay reduced to “instructor” rates. Academisation is starving authorities of vital central funds, and many of us are now quite determined that we will not be doing the same job for half the pay. The ensuing deterioration of standards is predictable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">. What role academy chains play . . .? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is nothing educational about the creation of academies and the inevitable chains that follow. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">They seem only to serve the interests of private industry. Motivated by money, or power, or winning league tables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> they have lost the original intention of education [from the Latin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">educere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to lead out], which is to consider the individual child, and his or her needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Here the media is particularly unhelpful, by using the new equivalents of “When did you stop beati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng your wife?” i.e. phrases like “failing schools”, “bottom of the tables” etc. You have to be in a school to understand how it works, and most of the public aren’t.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">6 The appropriateness of academy status for primaries</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">None at all. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">7. What alternative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">s to academy status  . .offered to failing primaries?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Firstly I would question who says they are failing, and sadly it seems someone with a vested interested in rubbishing the, keeping teachers in a state of fear, and someone looking for a school to steal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [and I do mean “steal”].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If a school [primary or 2ndary] is struggling, things are only made worse by drawing public attention to it. “Aspirational” parents will want to leave, demoralised teachers will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be less effective; things will be made worse. We ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed what we had before, a team of supportive HMIs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is an irony that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the very process which was publicly heralded as intended as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">curing the so-called failing schools has so much damage. Advice from teaching unions and other professionals was of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fered and ignored. The private sector was itching to get its hands on education, and the government was itching to appease big business.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The worst damage done by academisation is that broken link between schools/teachers who knew and were trusted by their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> students and families and the families themselves. Attending is the one legal obligation we ask, and here is the place, the interface wherein can be detected child abuse, illness, Special Needs, musical prodigy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Generations of trust wiped out by the abrup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t change of just member of staff, worse by the massive high turnover we now see, as teachers flee the incompetence of the academy system. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By measuring only what is barely measurable, Ofsted doesn’t see that bit of eye contact that makes way for a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disclosure, the home visit, the extra lifts to the hockey tournaments, well every</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as well as the teaching. Yet, when a child dies at its parents’ hands the public bays for teachers to be more accountable.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academisation has not narrowed the gap; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">combined with selective testing [and covert selection], it has widened it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [Apart from excessive exclusion, David Young Academy operates a system called “fair banding”, so that it does not need to take in all the local Seacroft kids. At Foxwood we took the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m all in – and listened to their stories], and Ofsted was invented we closed for public “low” rssults.]</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">No one person should have this role – intervening in individual schools. They don’t have the capacity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local authorities have seen their funding dry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">up as academies keep the pool of money that, collectively, once served a town.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The role of academy chains is to further reduce local accountability. The closer you are to a school, or a child, the more you care, and the more you try. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Victoria Jaquiss FRS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A, BA hons, PGCE, teacher, writer, bandleader</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Steel pan development officer and Head of Steel pans for Leeds ArtForms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Member of National Union of Teachers, Musicians Union, Anti-Academies Alliance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>